nformative assessment of Foucault’s relevance to theatre and performance studies and to our present cultural moment – it rereads his profound engagement with questions of truth, power and politics, in light of previously unknown writings and lectures set in relation to current political and cultural concerns. Unique to this volume is the discovery of a ‘theatrical’ Foucault - the profound affinity of his thinking with questions of performativity. This discovery makes accessible the ‘performance turn’ to readers of Foucault, while opening up ways of reading Foucault’s oeuvre ‘theatrically’.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPerforming artsxPhilosophy. 0aTheaterxPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Drama.2bisacsh  aMichel Foucault.  acultural history.  adramaturgy.  afilm.  aintroduction.  ajournalism.  alectures.  amusic.  aperformance studies.  aperformance turn.  aperformativity.  apolitics.  apower.  atheatre.  atruth.  awritings.1 aBononno, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElden, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Tony, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFoucault, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGotman, Kélina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGotman, Kélina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJordan, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicholls, Tracey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPauker, Magnolia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPellegrini, Ann, econtributor.4ctb